149 (2) (a) Any public library district listed in subdivision (1) of this subsection may, by
150 a majority vote of its board of directors, impose a tax not to exceed one-half of one cent on all
151 retail sales subject to taxation under sections 144.010 to 144.525 for the purpose of funding
152 the operation and maintenance of public libraries within the boundaries of such library
153 district. If the board of directors approves submitting a sales tax to the voters of the
154 library district, the governing body of the county shall comply.
155 (b) The tax authorized by this subsection shall be in addition to all other taxes
156 allowed by law. No tax under this subsection shall become effective unless the board of
157 directors submits to the voters of the district, at a county or state general, primary or special
158 election, a proposal to authorize the tax, and such tax shall become effective only after the
159 majority of the voters voting on such tax approve such tax.
160 2. In the event the district seeks to impose a sales tax under this subsection, the
161 question shall be submitted in substantially the following form:

HB 1621 6
162 Shall a ______ cent sales tax be levied on all retail sales within the
163 district for the purpose of providing funding for ______ library
164 district?
165 (cid:0) YES (cid:0) NO
166
167 If a majority of the votes cast on the proposal by the qualified voters voting thereon are in
168 favor of the proposal, then the tax shall become effective. If a majority of the votes cast by
169 the qualified voters voting are opposed to the proposal, then the board of directors shall have
170 no power to impose the tax unless and until another proposal to authorize the tax is submitted
171 to the voters of the district and such proposal is approved by a majority of the qualified voters
172 voting thereon. The provisions of sections 32.085 and 32.087 shall apply to any tax approved
173 under this subsection.
174 3. As used in this section, "qualified voters" or "voters" means any individuals
175 residing within the district who are eligible to be registered voters and who have registered to
176 vote under chapter 115, or, if no individuals are eligible and registered to vote reside within
177 the proposed district, all of the owners of real property located within the proposed district
178 who have unanimously petitioned for or consented to the adoption of an ordinance by the
179 governing body imposing a tax authorized in this section. If the owner of the property within
180 the proposed district is a political subdivision or corporation of the state, the governing body
181 of such political subdivision or corporation shall be considered the owner for purposes of this
182 section.
183 4. For purposes of this section the term "public library district" shall mean any city
184 library district, county library district, city-county library district, municipal library district,
185 consolidated library district, or urban library district.
